    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-icon" style="background:#1d6fa5;color:#fff;font-size:15px;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:.04em;">IM</div>
      <div>
        <div class="section-title">Internal Medicine</div>
        <div class="section-sub">The highest-volume room in the building &mdash; where the breathless patient lands first, and where the full PFT usually leaves the practice</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="imsub-nav">
      <button type="button" class="imsub-btn on" id="imsub-playbook" onclick="intmedShowView('playbook', this)">The Playbook</button>
      <button type="button" class="imsub-btn"    id="imsub-evidence" onclick="intmedShowView('evidence', this)">Evidence &amp; Billing</button>
    </div>

    <!-- ---------- VIEW 1: the rep's playbook ---------- -->
    <div id="intmed-view-playbook" class="im">
      <p class="im-lede">Internal medicine is not a specialty call &mdash; it is a <strong>volume</strong> call. Every chronic cough, every &ldquo;I get winded on the stairs,&rdquo; every long-time smoker and every pre-op clearance walks through this door first. Most of these practices own a spirometer and stop there. <strong>Everything past spirometry &mdash; lung volumes, DLCO &mdash; leaves as a referral</strong>, and with it the diagnosis, the follow-up visit, and the billing.</p>

      <div class="im-sec">
        <div class="im-sec-head"><span class="im-sec-num">01</span><span class="im-sec-title">The play, in five moves</span></div>
        <div class="im-steps">
          <div class="im-step"><div class="im-n">01</div><div>
            <h4>Do not open with the device. Open with the referral.</h4>
            <p>Ask what happens today when spirometry comes back abnormal or inconclusive. That answer is the whole sale. Every full-PFT referral is a patient who may never complete the workup and a study the practice never bills.</p>
            <span class="im-say">&ldquo;When spirometry looks off, where does that patient go next &mdash; and how many actually come back with the result?&rdquo;</span>
          </div></div>
          <div class="im-step"><div class="im-n">02</div><div>
            <h4>Name the population they already have</h4>
            <p>They are not being asked to find new patients. Chronic dyspnea, chronic cough, smoking history, asthma that never quite responds, pre-op clearance, heart-failure overlap &mdash; those charts are already on today&rsquo;s schedule.</p>
          </div></div>
          <div class="im-step"><div class="im-n">03</div><div>
            <h4>Make the guideline do the talking</h4>
            <p>COPD cannot be diagnosed without spirometry &mdash; GOLD requires a post-bronchodilator FEV<sub>1</sub>/FVC below 0.70. Asthma is supposed to be confirmed objectively, not on symptoms alone. This is not a PulmOne claim; it is the standard they are already held to.</p>
          </div></div>
          <div class="im-step"><div class="im-n">04</div><div>
            <h4>Show the complete test, then the gap</h4>
            <p>Spirometry alone is one code. A complete PFT is three &mdash; and it is the one that answers the question the referral was going to answer. Turn the screen to <strong>Evidence &amp; Billing</strong> and let the table land on its own.</p>
          </div></div>
          <div class="im-step"><div class="im-n">05</div><div>
            <h4>Close on staff, not on physicians</h4>
            <p>The objection is never the science &mdash; it is &ldquo;who runs it.&rdquo; A complete PFT on the MiniBox+ takes about 15&ndash;20 minutes and any trained staff member can operate it. Book the demo with the office manager in the room.</p>
          </div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="im-sec">
        <div class="im-sec-head"><span class="im-sec-num">02</span><span class="im-sec-title">Who is already on their schedule</span><span class="im-sec-note">Say these out loud &mdash; they will start naming patients</span></div>
        <div class="im-triggers">
          <div class="im-trigger"><span class="k">&mdash;</span><div>Chronic dyspnea on exertion with no clear cardiac cause</div></div>
          <div class="im-trigger"><span class="k">&mdash;</span><div>Chronic cough lasting more than eight weeks</div></div>
          <div class="im-trigger"><span class="k">&mdash;</span><div>Current or former smokers with any respiratory symptom</div></div>
          <div class="im-trigger"><span class="k">&mdash;</span><div>Asthma that keeps failing to respond to escalation</div></div>
          <div class="im-trigger"><span class="k">&mdash;</span><div>Heart-failure patients still breathless on optimal therapy</div></div>
          <div class="im-trigger"><span class="k">&mdash;</span><div>Pre-operative evaluation in patients with lung risk</div></div>
          <div class="im-trigger"><span class="k">&mdash;</span><div>Occupational or environmental exposure histories</div></div>
          <div class="im-trigger"><span class="k">&mdash;</span><div>Long-term amiodarone, methotrexate or other pulmonary-toxic therapy</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="im-sec">
        <div class="im-sec-head"><span class="im-sec-num">03</span><span class="im-sec-title">Discovery questions that open the room</span></div>
        <ul class="im-qs">
          <li>How many patients a week do you send out for a full PFT?
            <small>Anything above two or three a week already justifies the device on billing alone.</small></li>
          <li>What is the wait, and how many actually come back with the result?
            <small>The gap between &ldquo;referred&rdquo; and &ldquo;resulted&rdquo; is the pain point, not the wait itself.</small></li>
          <li>When you diagnose COPD, is it confirmed with spirometry every time?
            <small>Asked without judgment, this is the most productive question in the call.</small></li>
          <li>Who in the office runs the spirometer today?
            <small>Identify the operator early &mdash; that person will make or break adoption.</small></li>
          <li>If the complete study could be finished here in one visit, what would change?
            <small>Let them build the case themselves. Then get out of the way.</small></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="im-sec">
        <div class="im-sec-head"><span class="im-sec-num">04</span><span class="im-sec-title">Objection battlecard</span></div>
        <table class="im-obj">
          <thead><tr><th>What they say</th><th>What you say</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="q">&ldquo;We already have a spirometer.&rdquo;</td>
              <td>Good &mdash; you already believe in in-office testing. The MiniBox+ is not a replacement for that belief, it is the rest of the test: lung volumes and DLCO, the two things you currently have to refer out for.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="q">&ldquo;We just refer to pulmonology.&rdquo;</td>
              <td>You still can &mdash; with the study already in hand. The referral becomes a consult on a known result instead of a wait for one, and the patient does not fall out of the workup in between.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="q">&ldquo;Nobody here has time to run it.&rdquo;</td>
              <td>About 15&ndash;20 minutes, operated by any trained staff member, in a room you already have. Let your MA run one on me right now and time it yourself.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="q">&ldquo;I do not think it gets paid.&rdquo;</td>
              <td>A complete PFT is 94010 + 94726 + 94729 under the practice, national average around <span class="im-note" style="font-style:normal;font-weight:700;color:#1d6fa5;">$<span data-im-total>151.45</span></span> per patient when medically necessary. Open the Billing Helper and we will run your codes together.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="q">&ldquo;My patients are mostly healthy.&rdquo;</td>
              <td>Then we are not talking about screening them &mdash; and we should not be. This is for the symptomatic patient you are already working up. See the guardrail below; it protects the practice.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="im-sec">
        <div class="im-sec-head"><span class="im-sec-num">05</span><span class="im-sec-title">The line you do not cross</span></div>
        <div class="im-guard">
          <span class="k">Sell this correctly or not at all</span>
          <h4>Symptomatic workup is diagnostic. Asymptomatic testing is screening.</h4>
          <p>The USPSTF recommends <strong>against</strong> screening for COPD in asymptomatic adults &mdash; a grade D recommendation. Never pitch this device as a way to run PFTs on the whole panel, and never model volume off a screening program. It is not supported, it will not be paid, and it puts the practice at risk.</p>
          <p>What <em>is</em> supported: a patient with symptoms, an exposure history, or a disease being monitored. Documented symptoms and medical necessity are what make the study diagnostic &mdash; and payable.</p>
          <p class="im-note" style="color:#6a4a12;">Same landmine as the rheumatology tab. If a practice pushes for a screening model, walk it back to symptomatic workup and put it in writing.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="im-cta">
        <div>
          <div class="im-cta-h">Ready to hand across the desk</div>
          <div class="im-cta-s">Flip to Evidence &amp; Billing when the physician is in the room &mdash; the guideline case, the DLCO argument, and the complete-PFT billing on one screen.</div>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex; gap:8px; flex-wrap:wrap;">
          <button type="button" class="im-btn primary" onclick="intmedShowView('evidence', document.getElementById('imsub-evidence'))">Open Evidence &amp; Billing</button>
          <button type="button" class="im-btn" onclick="mbxOpenTab('billing')">Billing Helper</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><!-- /intmed-view-playbook -->

    <!-- ---------- VIEW 2: turn the screen around ---------- -->
    <div id="intmed-view-evidence" class="im" style="display:none">
      <p class="im-lede">Breathlessness, chronic cough and a smoking history are primary-care problems long before they are pulmonary ones. A <strong>complete PFT &mdash; spirometry, lung volumes and DLCO &mdash; done in-office in about 15&ndash;20 minutes</strong> answers the question on the same visit instead of exporting it. Every figure below comes from a named guideline or peer-reviewed source a physician can look up.</p>

      <div class="im-stats">
        <div class="im-stat"><div class="im-big">1 in 3</div><div class="im-lbl">adults carrying a physician diagnosis of asthma had no current asthma when objectively retested</div></div>
        <div class="im-stat"><div class="im-big">Post-BD</div><div class="im-lbl">spirometry showing FEV<sub>1</sub>/FVC &lt; 0.70 is <em>required</em> to diagnose COPD &mdash; there is no clinical shortcut</div></div>
        <div class="im-stat"><div class="im-big">15&ndash;20 min</div><div class="im-lbl">for the complete study, in your own office, run by trained staff</div></div>
      </div>

      <div class="im-sec">
        <div class="im-sec-head"><span class="im-sec-num">01</span><span class="im-sec-title">Where a complete PFT changes the internal medicine workup</span></div>
        <div class="im-grid2">
          <div class="im-card">
            <h4>COPD cannot be diagnosed without spirometry</h4>
            <p>GOLD requires a <b>post-bronchodilator FEV<sub>1</sub>/FVC below 0.70</b> to confirm persistent airflow limitation. Clinical impression alone produces both over- and under-diagnosis, and population studies consistently find that a large share of adults with airflow obstruction have never been given the diagnosis.</p>
            <span class="im-src">Source: GOLD Global Strategy for the Diagnosis, Management and Prevention of COPD (current report).</span>
          </div>
          <div class="im-card">
            <h4>Asthma is supposed to be confirmed objectively</h4>
            <p>NAEPP and GINA both call for spirometry to establish the diagnosis &mdash; symptoms and treatment response alone are unreliable. On formal reassessment, <b>about one third</b> of adults carrying a physician diagnosis of asthma did not have current asthma.</p>
            <span class="im-src">Sources: Aaron SD et&nbsp;al., Reevaluation of Diagnosis in Adults With Physician-Diagnosed Asthma, JAMA 2017;317(3):269&ndash;279; NAEPP EPR-3 and 2020 Focused Updates; GINA report.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="im-card">
            <h4>Chronic dyspnea and chronic cough</h4>
            <p>Cardiac and pulmonary disease are the likeliest causes of chronic breathlessness, and spirometry is a recommended <b>first-line</b> test in that workup. Adding lung volumes and DLCO separates obstruction, restriction and gas-exchange disease in a single sitting.</p>
            <span class="im-src">Source: Chronic Dyspnea: Diagnosis and Evaluation, Am Fam Physician 2020;101(9):542&ndash;548.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="im-card">
            <h4>Baseline before risk &mdash; surgery and drug therapy</h4>
            <p>A documented baseline supports peri-operative risk discussion in patients with known or suspected lung disease, and gives a reference point for patients on therapies with recognized pulmonary toxicity. <span class="im-note">A baseline informs risk; it is not a pass/fail clearance test.</span></p>
            <span class="im-src">Use for symptomatic or at-risk patients with a documented indication &mdash; not as a routine pre-op screen.</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="im-dlco">
          <span class="k">The full-PFT difference</span>
          <h4>DLCO &mdash; what a spirometer structurally cannot see</h4>
          <p>Spirometry measures airflow. It does not measure how much lung there is, and it does not measure gas exchange. <b>Lung volumes</b> distinguish true restriction from an obstructive pattern; <b>DLCO</b> reflects the alveolar-capillary surface &mdash; which is where interstitial disease, emphysema and pulmonary vascular disease announce themselves, often while spirometry still looks acceptable. A normal spirometry with a low DLCO is a finding, not a reassurance, and it is precisely the result that would otherwise have required the referral.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="im-sec">
        <div class="im-sec-head"><span class="im-sec-num">02</span><span class="im-sec-title">What the complete study bills &mdash; in your office</span></div>
        <table class="im-bill">
          <thead><tr><th>CPT</th><th>Component</th><th>Nat&rsquo;l avg</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="have"><td class="code">94010</td><td>Spirometry &mdash; what most practices already bill</td><td><span class="cpt-rate" data-cpt-rate="94010">$27.34</span></td></tr>
            <tr class="gap"><td class="code">94726</td><td>Lung volumes (plethysmography) &mdash; today, this is the referral</td><td><span class="cpt-rate" data-cpt-rate="94726">$55.72</span></td></tr>
            <tr class="gap"><td class="code">94729</td><td>DLCO (diffusing capacity) &mdash; today, this is the referral</td><td><span class="cpt-rate" data-cpt-rate="94729">$59.87</span></td></tr>
            <tr class="total"><td></td><td>Complete PFT, per patient</td><td>~$<span data-im-total>151.45</span></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="im-disc" style="margin-top:8px;"><b>Add-ons when medically necessary:</b> 94060 pre/post bronchodilator (<span class="cpt-rate" data-cpt-rate="94060">$38.80</span>) &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; 94375 flow-volume loop (<span class="cpt-rate" data-cpt-rate="94375">$39.11</span>). Note that 94060 already includes 94010 &mdash; the two are bundled and cannot both be billed for the same session. Billed under the practice: the study, the result and the revenue all stay in-house. <span class="rates-stamp">Rates current as of <span class="rates-asof">&mdash;</span></span> Every dollar figure on this page is drawn live from the toolkit&rsquo;s single rate source &mdash; the <b>Billing Helper</b> owns the rates; nothing here is typed in by hand.</p>

        <div class="im-guard" style="margin-top:16px;">
          <span class="k">Coverage guardrail</span>
          <h4>Diagnostic, not screening</h4>
          <p>The USPSTF recommends <b>against</b> screening asymptomatic adults for COPD (grade D). Pulmonary function testing here is appropriate for the <b>symptomatic patient being worked up</b>, the patient with a relevant exposure or risk history, or a diagnosed condition being monitored &mdash; with the indication documented. Asymptomatic screening is not supported and should not be billed as diagnostic.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="im-sec">
        <div class="im-sec-head"><span class="im-sec-num">03</span><span class="im-sec-title">Run the numbers on this practice</span></div>
        <div class="im-cta">
          <div>
            <div class="im-cta-h">ROI, financing and coding &mdash; live, on their volume</div>
            <div class="im-cta-s">Enter their real referral count and show payback in weeks, or open the Billing Helper and walk their codes and documentation line by line.</div>
          </div>
          <div style="display:flex; gap:8px; flex-wrap:wrap;">
            <button type="button" class="im-btn primary" onclick="mbxOpenTab('financing')">ROI &amp; Financing</button>
            <button type="button" class="im-btn" onclick="mbxOpenTab('billing')">Billing Helper</button>
            <button type="button" class="im-btn" onclick="mbxOpenTab('interpretation')">PFT Interpretation</button>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="im-disc"><b>Billing &amp; coding:</b> CPT selection must be based on medical necessity and the documented indication; reimbursement is subject to individual health-plan policy and geography. All dollar figures are Medicare national averages shown for discussion only and are refreshed from the toolkit&rsquo;s single rate source &mdash; verify against the current CMS fee schedule, which updates each January. Device timing (~15&ndash;20 minutes for a complete PFT) reflects PulmOne product materials. Clinical statements above are drawn from the named guidelines and publications and are not a substitute for clinical judgment.</p>
    </div><!-- /intmed-view-evidence -->
  </div>

