      #tab-allergy .alp-files-cta-btns button.ghost { background:#fff; color:var(--alt-deep); border:1.5px solid var(--alt); }
      @media(max-width:720px){ #tab-allergy .alp-grid2, #tab-allergy .alp-stats, #tab-allergy .alp-cov { grid-template-columns:1fr; } #tab-allergy .alp-files-cta { flex-direction:column; align-items:stretch; } #tab-allergy .alp-files-cta-btns button { flex:1 1 auto; } }
    </style>

    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-icon" style="background:#0b6e4d;color:#fff;">&#127793;</div>
      <div>
        <div class="section-title">Allergy / Immunology</div>
        <div class="section-sub">The complete allergy &amp; asthma resource &mdash; the play, the coverage &amp; coding, the calculators, and every file ready to email</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="alsub-nav">
      <button type="button" class="alsub-btn on" id="alsub-playbook" onclick="allergyShowView('playbook', this)">&#128214; The Playbook</button>
      <button type="button" class="alsub-btn"    id="alsub-calcs"    onclick="allergyShowView('calcs', this)">&#129518; Calculators</button>
      <button type="button" class="alsub-btn"    id="alsub-files"    onclick="allergyShowView('files', this)">&#128193; Files &amp; Templates</button>
    </div>

    <div id="allergy-view-playbook" class="alp">
      <div class="alp-files-cta">
        <div>
          <div class="alp-files-cta-h">&#128193; Everything for the allergy call &mdash; ready to email</div>
          <div class="alp-files-cta-s">The &ldquo;Will You Get Paid?&rdquo; coverage &amp; coding guide, the brochure, the CHEST 2021 validation, the sample report, plus the ROI, financing &amp; PFT-coding calculators &mdash; every file and tool in one place.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="alp-files-cta-btns">
          <button type="button" onclick="allergyShowView('files', document.getElementById('alsub-files'))">Open the files</button>
          <button type="button" class="ghost" onclick="allergyEmailAll()">&#9993; Email the allergy pack</button>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="alp-lede">Most allergy practices run <strong>spirometry only</strong>. Everything past that &mdash; lung volumes, DLCO &mdash; goes out the door as a referral, and with it the patient, the follow-through, and the billing. MiniBox+ closes that gap in the same exam room they already use.</div>

      <div class="alp-sec">
        <div class="alp-sec-head"><span class="alp-sec-num">01</span><span class="alp-sec-title">The play, in five moves</span></div>
        <div class="alp-steps">
          <div class="alp-step"><div class="alp-n">1</div><div><h4>Start at the spirometer they already own</h4><p>They believe in in-office testing &mdash; they&rsquo;re doing it every day. The pitch isn&rsquo;t &ldquo;start testing,&rdquo; it&rsquo;s &ldquo;finish the test you already started.&rdquo;</p></div></div>
          <div class="alp-step"><div class="alp-n">2</div><div><h4>Find the referral leak</h4><p>Ask what happens after an abnormal or inconclusive spirometry. Every full-PFT referral is a patient who may never complete the workup &mdash; and a visit their practice doesn&rsquo;t bill.</p></div></div>
          <div class="alp-step"><div class="alp-n">3</div><div><h4>Lead with the hero line</h4><p><strong>&ldquo;Keep your asthma patients in-house with full PFTs &mdash; not just spirometry. One device. One visit. Full 94010 + 94726 + 94729 billing.&rdquo;</strong></p></div></div>
          <div class="alp-step"><div class="alp-n">4</div><div><h4>Make the clinical case with air trapping</h4><p>Asthma/COPD overlap patients need lung volumes to separate obstruction from restriction &mdash; and detecting air trapping changes the prescription. Spirometry alone can&rsquo;t see it.</p></div></div>
          <div class="alp-step"><div class="alp-n">5</div><div><h4>Close on their own volume</h4><p>Run the ROI calculator at their current spirometry volume and show the incremental 94726/94729 revenue per visit. The demo confirms; the math closes.</p></div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alp-sec">
        <div class="alp-sec-head"><span class="alp-sec-num">02</span><span class="alp-sec-title">Why it lands</span></div>
        <div class="alp-stats">
          <div class="alp-stat"><div class="alp-big">1 visit</div><div class="alp-lbl">spirometry, lung volumes, and DLCO at the appointment the patient already made</div></div>
          <div class="alp-stat"><div class="alp-big">+2 codes</div><div class="alp-lbl">94726 + 94729 added on top of the spirometry they bill today</div></div>
          <div class="alp-stat"><div class="alp-big">No booth</div><div class="alp-lbl">exam-room footprint &mdash; no sealed box, no dedicated PFT tech</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alp-sec">
        <div class="alp-sec-head"><span class="alp-sec-num">03</span><span class="alp-sec-title">Will you get paid? &mdash; the coverage answer</span></div>
        <div class="alp-cov">
          <div class="alp-cov-card"><span class="alp-cov-tag yes">Yes</span><div class="alp-cov-q">Will insurers pay for it?</div><div class="alp-cov-a">Spirometry (94010), reversibility (94060), lung volumes (94726) and DLCO (94729) are routine, long-established codes. Medicare pays whenever medical necessity is charted, and the major commercial payers &mdash; UnitedHealthcare, Aetna, Cigna, BCBS, Humana &mdash; follow the same framework.</div></div>
          <div class="alp-cov-card"><span class="alp-cov-tag no">No hard cap</span><div class="alp-cov-q">How often can they test?</div><div class="alp-cov-a">There is <strong>no national frequency cap</strong>. The old &ldquo;about once a year&rdquo; figure came from Medicare&rsquo;s standalone PFT policy, which was <strong>retired in November 2023</strong> &mdash; it still circulates widely and is obsolete. What governs now: testing is supported at diagnosis, at each meaningful change in control or therapy, and to confirm response. Repeat testing needs documented clinical change; routine testing at every office visit is expressly not reimbursable.</div></div>
          <div class="alp-cov-card"><span class="alp-cov-tag watch">Watch</span><div class="alp-cov-q">When is prior auth needed?</div><div class="alp-cov-a">Commercial plans typically want prior authorization above roughly 2&ndash;3 panels a year. A bronchial challenge (94070 / 95070) is payable when baseline spirometry is normal but asthma is still suspected.</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alp-sec">
        <div class="alp-sec-head"><span class="alp-sec-num">04</span><span class="alp-sec-title">Who to test &amp; how to code it</span></div>

        <div class="alp-grp">1 &middot; Confirmed asthma &amp; airway diagnoses <span>&mdash; recurring revenue</span></div>
        <div class="alp-tbl-wrap"><table class="alp-tbl">
          <thead><tr><th>Qualifying diagnosis</th><th>ICD-10</th><th>Bill (CPT)</th><th>Frequency you can support</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Allergic asthma, mild&ndash;moderate persistent</td><td class="alp-icd">J45.30/.31, J45.40/.41</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 / 94010</td><td>At dx, each step change; 1&ndash;2&times;/yr stable; full panel when a biologic or alternate dx is considered</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Severe persistent / difficult to control</td><td class="alp-icd">J45.40/.41, J45.50/.51</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 / 94726 / 94729</td><td>More frequent monitoring; full panel including lung volumes + DLCO</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Exercise-induced / cough-variant</td><td class="alp-icd">J45.990/.991, J45.52</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 / 94726 / 94729</td><td>Add methacholine challenge (94070 / 95070) when baseline spirometry is normal</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Asthma&ndash;COPD overlap</td><td class="alp-icd">J44.9 / J45.909</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 / 94726 / 94729</td><td>Full PFT with DLCO to separate reversible obstruction from emphysema; periodic</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Uncontrolled / recent exacerbation</td><td class="alp-icd">J45.901 / J45.902</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 / 94010</td><td>At each significant change in control or after an exacerbation</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table></div>
        <div class="alp-tbl-cap">Bill <b>94060</b> when a bronchodilator is given (it already includes the spirometry); bill <b>94010</b> alone for follow-up spirometry. Add <b>94726</b> + <b>94729</b> for a full panel. <b>Never bill 94010 and 94060 on the same date.</b></div>

        <div style="display:flex;gap:11px;align-items:flex-start;border:1px solid #e6c98a;border-left:4px solid #c98b1d;background:#fffaf0;border-radius:10px;padding:13px 16px;margin:12px 0 0;">
          <span style="font-size:16px;line-height:1;flex-shrink:0;">&#9888;&#65039;</span>
          <div style="font-size:12.5px;color:#5a5a5a;line-height:1.6;">
            <div style="font-size:13px;font-weight:800;color:#9a6510;margin-bottom:3px;">Three traps that deny allergy PFT claims</div>
            <b>1. Do not bill 94640 for the puff.</b> The bronchodilator administration is already inside 94060 &mdash; NCCI bundles 94640 into it, and CMS calls billing it separately a misuse of the code. The drug itself may be billed via its J code if the practice bought it.<br>
            <b>2. Allergic rhinitis will not carry the claim.</b> J30.x does not appear on the MAC covered-diagnosis list for pulmonary function testing. Code the asthma or the respiratory symptom as primary; rhinitis and atopy are secondary context only.<br>
            <b>3. FeNO (95012) has no coverage policy at all.</b> No NCD, no LCD anywhere. Several commercial plans still deny it as investigational, and it has no physician work value, so it is office-setting only. Treat it as a clinical add-on, never as assumed revenue.<br>
            <span style="color:#7a7a7a;">Also worth charting: reversibility needs all four elements &mdash; pre values, agent and dose, the wait interval, post values &mdash; plus a signed interpretation. Missing post-bronchodilator numbers is the single most common 94060 denial. Note that two reversibility thresholds are in play: the classic <b>&ge;12% and &gt;200&nbsp;mL</b> that most payer policies still reference, and the newer ERS/ATS 2022 <b>&gt;10% of predicted</b>. If you interpret by the 2022 standard, say so in the report.</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="alp-grp">2 &middot; Symptom-driven <span>&mdash; no confirmed diagnosis needed</span></div>
        <div class="alp-tbl-wrap"><table class="alp-tbl">
          <thead><tr><th>Presenting symptom</th><th>ICD-10</th><th>Bill (CPT)</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Shortness of breath / dyspnea</td><td class="alp-icd">R06.00</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 / 94726 / 94729</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Wheezing</td><td class="alp-icd">R06.2</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 / 94010</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chronic / unspecified cough</td><td class="alp-icd">R05.3 / R05.9</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 &mdash; or 94070 + 95070 for a challenge</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table></div>
        <div class="alp-tbl-cap">Code the symptom as primary, add the known allergic condition (rhinitis, atopy) as secondary. Billed once per episode &mdash; if asthma is confirmed, the patient moves to Group 1 and becomes recurring revenue.</div>

        <div class="alp-grp">3 &middot; Therapy monitoring <span>&mdash; controllers &amp; biologics</span></div>
        <div class="alp-tbl-wrap"><table class="alp-tbl">
          <thead><tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Pair with</th><th>Bill (CPT)</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Controller step-up &mdash; before/after starting or escalating ICS / LABA</td><td class="alp-icd">Asthma Dx</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 &mdash; pre/post documents the step-up was warranted and is working</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Biologic candidate or on a biologic (omalizumab, mepolizumab, dupilumab, benralizumab, tezepelumab)</td><td class="alp-icd">Asthma Dx + Z79.51</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">Baseline + periodic PFT; add FeNO (95012) for T2 / eosinophilic phenotyping</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chronic systemic steroid use &mdash; frequent OCS bursts or maintenance prednisone</td><td class="alp-icd">Asthma Dx + Z79.52 / Z79.899</td><td class="alp-cpt-in">94060 / 94726 / 94729 &mdash; the strongest case for a full panel</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table></div>
      </div>

      <div class="alp-sec">
        <div class="alp-sec-head"><span class="alp-sec-num">05</span><span class="alp-sec-title">The one charting habit that gets it paid</span></div>
        <div class="alp-hab">
          <h4>Pair the right ICD-10 with one sentence of rationale &mdash; and append modifier 25.</h4>
          <p>Match the asthma type &amp; severity (or the presenting symptom) to the visit, write <b>one sentence</b> of clinical rationale in the chart, and append <b>modifier 25</b> to a same-day office visit. That single habit is what gets the claim paid &mdash; and protects it from a later audit. Coverage is ultimately set by each patient&rsquo;s payer, plan, and Medicare Administrative Contractor (MAC); verify the local LCD before billing.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alp-sec">
        <div class="alp-sec-head"><span class="alp-sec-num">06</span><span class="alp-sec-title">Four questions that open the call</span></div>
        <div class="alp-qs">
          <div class="alp-qitem"><p>When spirometry comes back normal but the patient is still symptomatic &mdash; what&rsquo;s your next step today?</p></div>
          <div class="alp-qitem"><p>How many of the patients you refer out for full PFTs actually complete the appointment?</p></div>
          <div class="alp-qitem"><p>How many spirometries is the practice running in a typical week?</p></div>
          <div class="alp-qitem alp-closer"><span class="alp-qtag">The closer</span><p>If you could run the full PFT in this exam room at today&rsquo;s visit &mdash; how many of those referrals would you keep in-house?</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alp-sec">
        <div class="alp-sec-head"><span class="alp-sec-num">07</span><span class="alp-sec-title">Quick reference</span></div>
        <div class="alp-grid2">
          <div class="alp-ref">
            <h4>The upgrade, in codes</h4>
            <div class="alp-cpt"><span class="alp-cpt-code">94010</span><span class="alp-cpt-desc">Spirometry &mdash; what they bill today</span></div>
            <div class="alp-cpt"><span class="alp-cpt-code">94060</span><span class="alp-cpt-desc">Spirometry, pre &amp; post bronchodilator</span></div>
            <div class="alp-cpt"><span class="alp-cpt-code">94726</span><span class="alp-cpt-desc">Lung volumes / plethysmography (TLC) &mdash; <b>added</b></span></div>
            <div class="alp-cpt"><span class="alp-cpt-code">94729</span><span class="alp-cpt-desc">DLCO (diffusing capacity) &mdash; <b>added</b></span></div>
            <div class="alp-note"><b>Current dollar rates</b> live in the CPT &amp; Revenue tab and the Billing Helper &mdash; quote from there so the numbers are always current.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="alp-ref">
            <h4>The three objections, answered</h4>
            <div class="alp-obj"><div class="alp-q">&ldquo;We just send them for a formal PFT.&rdquo;</div><div class="alp-a">How many actually go? Every no-show referral is an incomplete workup and a lost billable visit. MiniBox+ captures them at the appointment they already kept.</div></div>
            <div class="alp-obj"><div class="alp-q">&ldquo;My staff can&rsquo;t run complex PFTs.&rdquo;</div><div class="alp-a">If they run a spirometer, they can run this &mdash; MiniBox+ was built for exam-room use, coached and scored on-screen, results to the EMR in minutes.</div></div>
            <div class="alp-obj"><div class="alp-q">&ldquo;We don&rsquo;t have the space.&rdquo;</div><div class="alp-a">That&rsquo;s the point &mdash; there is no booth. MiniBox+ lives on a cart in the exam room you already have.</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alp-sec">
        <div class="alp-sec-head"><span class="alp-sec-num">08</span><span class="alp-sec-title">The ask</span></div>
        <div class="alp-ref" style="border-left:4px solid var(--alg);">
          <div style="font-size:14px; font-weight:700; color:var(--alink); margin-bottom:4px;">Demo + ROI calc at their current spirometry volume.</div>
          <div style="font-size:13px; color:var(--alsoft); line-height:1.55;">Show the incremental 94726/94729 revenue on the numbers they already produce. The brochure and clinical evidence pack are ready to send from the <strong>&#9993; Email Library</strong>.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><!-- end allergy-view-playbook -->

    <!-- ============ VIEW: CALCULATORS ============ -->
    <div id="allergy-view-calcs" class="alp" style="display:none;">
      <div class="alp-lede">Three interactive tools for the allergy call &mdash; run them live in the exam room or send them ahead. <strong>Open</strong> launches the tool in a new tab, <strong>Download</strong> saves it, <strong>Email it</strong> sends it as a working file the practice opens in their own browser (works offline). The ROI calculator is the closer &mdash; plug in their weekly spirometry volume and show the added 94726/94729 revenue.</div>
